U.S. stocks ended lower on Monday in a year set to leave investors with significant returns, buoyed by a preliminary trade deal with China and policy support from the Federal Reserve. The S&P 500 SPX, +0.22% was down 0.6% to end around 3,221. The Dow Jones Industrial Average DJIA, +0.58% shed 183 points, or 0.6%, to finish near 28,462, based on preliminary numbers. The Nasdaq Composite COMP, +0.51% closed 0.7% lower to 8,946, posting its second straight loss. To be sure, all three major stock benchmarks are inches away from their record closes. News reports said Chinese Vice-Premier Liu He could travel to Washington on Saturday to sign the phase one trade deal. In corporate news, shares of Tesla Inc. TSLA, +4.76% retreated 3.8% after a Cowen analyst expected fewer car deliveries than the automaker's forecasts for 2019.